## When to use
When you need to frequently monitor the disk usage of specific directories or files and want a quick way to do so from your terminal.

## Approach
Create a shell function in your `.bashrc` file that uses the `du` tool to quickly check disk usage. This function can be tailored to provide summary output for a given directory.

## Example
Edit your `~/.bashrc` file and add the following:

```shell
function disk_usage() {
    du -sh "$@" | sort -h;
}
```

After adding this, reload your `.bashrc` with `source ~/.bashrc`. You can now use `disk_usage /path/to/directory` to get a sorted summary of directory contents by size.

## Pitfalls
- Ensure the function name does not conflict with existing commands or functions in your environment.
- The `sort -h` part assumes that `sort` supports human-readable sorting which may vary across systems.